WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.210 --> 00:00:02.668
STEPHEN CARPENTER: I thought
these three questions could be

00:00:02.668 --> 00:00:04.915
part of our conversation later.

00:00:04.915 --> 00:00:09.967
I want us to get up and
actually create a public work.

00:00:09.967 --> 00:00:11.550
But I've been thinking
about how might

00:00:11.550 --> 00:00:13.560
contemporary art
and social practice

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:15.930
enable conversations
about difficult subjects?

00:00:15.930 --> 00:00:19.650
And that's part of what
we're interested in.

00:00:19.650 --> 00:00:23.150
Couldn't that be the
focus of a curriculum?

00:00:23.150 --> 00:00:27.860
A multi-week, a
multi-session unit

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:33.020
of instruction with
learners of a range of ages

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:35.210
and in the range of spaces.

00:00:35.210 --> 00:00:37.287
Or why prepare
teachers as agents

00:00:37.287 --> 00:00:38.370
of positive social change?

00:00:38.370 --> 00:00:40.080
I mean, some people say, oh, we
have to prepare them for that,

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:41.104
but why?

00:00:41.104 --> 00:00:42.270
What would come out of that?

00:00:42.270 --> 00:00:43.850
Or why not, right?

00:00:43.850 --> 00:00:44.600
What does it mean?

00:00:44.600 --> 00:00:45.974
Maybe the question
should be what

00:00:45.974 --> 00:00:48.890
does it mean for
teachers to be prepared

00:00:48.890 --> 00:00:52.010
as agents for social change?

00:00:52.010 --> 00:00:56.270
Some of you are studying in
departments or programs, where

00:00:56.270 --> 00:00:59.780
social change, social activism,
positive social responsibility

00:00:59.780 --> 00:01:02.390
is central to the mission.

00:01:02.390 --> 00:01:04.730
Why do that?

00:01:04.730 --> 00:01:07.780
Is that such a good thing?

00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:10.240
Or how can creative
responses to social injustice

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:12.160
interrupt conditions
of inequality?

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:14.540
We might not be
able to change them.

00:01:14.540 --> 00:01:15.910
Might not be able to stop them.

00:01:15.910 --> 00:01:18.190
But maybe it interrupts
it just long enough

00:01:18.190 --> 00:01:20.800
to reposition or find
other ways, other tactics,

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:23.610
other approaches to engage.

00:01:23.610 --> 00:01:25.110
I think this is a
good time to stop.

00:01:25.110 --> 00:01:30.620
And let's get up, and let's
make some public trouble.

00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:35.330
I brought with me
some children's books.

00:01:35.330 --> 00:01:37.920
And I also brought
some children's toys.

00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:41.290
How many of you
brought cellphones?

00:01:41.290 --> 00:01:43.600
How many of those
cellphones take pictures?

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:44.530
Oh, yeah.

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:46.330
Now we can work as individuals.

00:01:46.330 --> 00:01:49.520
We can work in pairs
or trios, if we want.

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:50.260
All right?

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:51.970
I have some
children's books here.

00:01:51.970 --> 00:01:54.220
I'll share them--
show these to you.

00:01:54.220 --> 00:01:57.760
Not all of them deal with
uncomfortable stories.

00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:00.256
Some of them do.

00:02:00.256 --> 00:02:02.380
There's a whole range of
things, like Flat Stanley.

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:03.550
I don't know if you know
of the Flat Stanley.

00:02:03.550 --> 00:02:05.415
To me, there's a Henry
Box Brown deal here,

00:02:05.415 --> 00:02:07.540
where you can mail individuals
to different places.

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:09.940
Here, he's pretty happy about
going to visit his family.

00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:12.550
But Henry couldn't do that.

00:02:12.550 --> 00:02:17.980
Or The Big Orange Splot,
this is about one house

00:02:17.980 --> 00:02:20.500
being different.

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:22.900
And then I won't ruin the
story for you at the end,

00:02:22.900 --> 00:02:25.437
but it's about
finding your own way.

00:02:25.437 --> 00:02:27.020
Little Blue and
Little Yellow, I don't

00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:28.680
know if you know this story.

00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:30.680
But when you mix blue and
yellow, you get green.

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:32.770
And what does it mean
to be blue or yellow?

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:34.410
And how does mixing happen?

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:37.089
Tar Beach, about a
little girl who--

00:02:37.089 --> 00:02:39.130
she doesn't have something
or can't go somewhere.

00:02:39.130 --> 00:02:41.290
She just imagines that
she can fly there,

00:02:41.290 --> 00:02:43.600
and she can capture
that experience.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:46.750
Bell Hooks-- I don't know if you
know her children's book, Skin

00:02:46.750 --> 00:02:48.610
Again.

00:02:48.610 --> 00:02:53.740
There's a wonderful book about
learning disabilities, reading,

00:02:53.740 --> 00:02:55.700
in particular.

00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:58.210
And it's called The
Art of Miss Chew, where

00:02:58.210 --> 00:03:00.640
the art teacher,
her art teacher,

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:04.860
essentially figured out she was
seeing the world differently.

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:08.520
Her reading-- and
she was reading

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:11.402
the spaces between the words,
not the words themselves.

00:03:11.402 --> 00:03:13.860
Just like an artist might try
to render the negative space,

00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:16.170
rather than the positive space.

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:20.250
Or a Maya Angelou poem and a
Jean-Michel Basquiat poem put

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:21.662
together--

00:03:21.662 --> 00:03:25.830
or Jean-Michel Basquiat images
and a Maya Angelou poem, Life

00:03:25.830 --> 00:03:27.060
Doesn't Frighten Me Anymore.

00:03:27.060 --> 00:03:30.720
These are children's books
that I found kids respond to

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:32.230
in interesting ways.

00:03:32.230 --> 00:03:35.190
So you might choose
one of these books

00:03:35.190 --> 00:03:39.720
and find one of those
unexpected public spaces,

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:42.300
where you don't think education
or art, making your art

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:44.220
practice, is supposed to happen.

00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:46.080
You could take one
of these books,

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:50.070
and go and read
it there out loud.

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:54.030
And have somebody else or
yourself video tape you or--

00:03:54.030 --> 00:03:56.640
not video tape, you
can tell how old I am.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:03:57.240
What is it?

00:03:57.240 --> 00:04:00.330
Make a video, a
mobile video of you.

00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:02.330
And you can put one
of the hashtags.

00:04:02.330 --> 00:04:03.710
Where are our hashtags, Steve?

00:04:03.710 --> 00:04:04.890
Here it is.

00:04:04.890 --> 00:04:07.510
You can hashtag it, and
pop it up on social media,

00:04:07.510 --> 00:04:08.790
if you'd like.

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:11.530
Or you can take still
photo of yourself

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:14.161
or someone else
reading out loud.

00:04:14.161 --> 00:04:15.160
Or you can take several.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:17.140
Document that experience.

00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:19.360
What would be interesting
is to see what kind

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:20.827
of social interaction happens.

00:04:20.827 --> 00:04:22.035
And think about the critique.

00:04:22.035 --> 00:04:23.830
Remember those little
tiny townspeople

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:25.120
and the tiny presidents?

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:27.940
The critiques of
then the stories

00:04:27.940 --> 00:04:31.280
of the little people and
the stories of those spaces.

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:32.840
There's a conversation
that happens.

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:35.770
Think about the story you
might read in that space

00:04:35.770 --> 00:04:37.400
in relationship to that space.

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:42.490
Or I have these little toys,
just three firefighters,

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:47.980
two of whom have razor stub
and one has a mustache.

00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:51.940
I wonder how gendered this is.

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:54.590
I'm just asking
questions right now.

00:04:54.590 --> 00:04:57.040
Or little animals.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:04:58.630
Or I have little
Lego mini figures.

00:04:58.630 --> 00:04:59.710
These have to be put together.

00:04:59.710 --> 00:05:02.168
I mean, you're welcome to take
them, and put them together,

00:05:02.168 --> 00:05:06.640
and use them in the ways that
you saw in the photographs,

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:11.290
critiquing, having a
conversation in a public space.

00:05:11.290 --> 00:05:13.870
That story-- where's
my-- oh, there it is,

00:05:13.870 --> 00:05:14.770
Henry's Freedom Box.

00:05:14.770 --> 00:05:16.728
I think I'm going to take
one of these pallets.

00:05:16.728 --> 00:05:18.390
I can't take both of them.

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:19.900
I'm going to take one of
these, and I'm going outside.

00:05:19.900 --> 00:05:21.250
I'm going to read
this book outside.

00:05:21.250 --> 00:05:22.916
I'm going to perform
that story outside.

00:05:27.817 --> 00:05:29.220
Henry was lonely.

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:33.870
One day, he met Nancy, who
was shopping for her mistress.

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:37.016
They walked, and talked,
and agreed to meet again.

00:05:37.016 --> 00:05:38.870
Henry felt like singing.

00:05:38.870 --> 00:05:42.110
But slaves didn't dare
sing in the streets.

00:05:42.110 --> 00:05:45.020
Instead, he hummed
all the way home.

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:47.300
Henry knew they were very lucky.

00:05:47.300 --> 00:05:50.220
They lived together, even though
they had different masters.

