STUDENT 1: "Life doesn't
frighten me at all, not at all.

00:06:08.386 --> 00:06:09.830
Life doesn't
frighten me at all."

00:06:12.265 --> 00:06:12.806
Thanks a lot.

00:06:12.806 --> 00:06:14.440
GIRL: Well, what's this for?

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:16.839
STUDENT 1: Oh, it's a class
assignment I'm having.

00:06:16.839 --> 00:06:17.380
GIRL: Oh, OK.

00:06:17.380 --> 00:06:18.850
I noticed there are some
other people as well.

00:06:18.850 --> 00:06:19.158
STUDENT 1: There are
a couple other people

00:06:19.158 --> 00:06:20.810
doing the same thing.

00:06:20.810 --> 00:06:22.280
GIRL: [LAUGHS]

00:06:22.280 --> 00:06:24.730
STUDENT 2: "The house was
looking like it was green."

00:06:33.012 --> 00:06:34.470
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Does anyone want

00:06:34.470 --> 00:06:37.770
to talk about-- you want to
talk about your own specific

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:42.090
experience, either reading
a book out loud in public

00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:46.830
or reading a public space in
conversation with your figure?

00:06:46.830 --> 00:06:50.280
STUDENT 2: Mainly,
people ignored me.

00:06:50.280 --> 00:06:53.490
Some people, like you
said, made sort of a wide--

00:06:53.490 --> 00:06:56.820
somebody came, realized
they were sort of

00:06:56.820 --> 00:06:59.150
in the scope of the photograph.

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:00.820
And oh, I'm so sorry.

00:07:00.820 --> 00:07:01.470
Oh.

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:04.031
And you were taking
a photograph,

00:07:04.031 --> 00:07:05.280
and you said, no, no, it's OK.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:06.000
You can go in.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.330
No, no, no, I'm good.

00:07:08.330 --> 00:07:10.230
So that was interesting.

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:14.280
I used to love to read
children's books to my kids.

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:16.230
So I mean, it was
just so much fun

00:07:16.230 --> 00:07:18.340
to be out there and
showing everybody.

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:21.320
And some people looked
at me, like oh, OK.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:23.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:24.480
And some people smiled.

00:07:24.480 --> 00:07:27.425
And I saw people sort of taking
pictures as they walked by.

00:07:27.425 --> 00:07:28.590
STEPHEN CARPENTER: They looked
stealth at the time, right?

00:07:28.590 --> 00:07:30.054
STUDENT 2: [LAUGHS] Exactly.

00:07:30.054 --> 00:07:31.470
And then I was
watching you, and I

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:36.120
saw somebody doing posing off
to the side in front of you,

00:07:36.120 --> 00:07:38.250
like wanting to have a picture.

00:07:38.250 --> 00:07:40.840
They figured this
was some thing.

00:07:40.840 --> 00:07:43.200
And they wanted to be in
it, but not really in it.

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:45.670
So they were off on the
side, posing while you--

00:07:45.670 --> 00:07:46.417
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:46.417 --> 00:07:48.000
STUDENT 3: That
fascinates me, though.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.416
If you don't even
know what it is,

00:07:49.416 --> 00:07:51.690
why are you so desperate
to get a picture?

00:07:51.690 --> 00:07:53.880
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Nicholas
Mirzoeff, visual culture

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:59.520
scholar, uses the
word "sublime" to talk

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:04.200
about those visual moments,
or those moments that are so

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:07.140
repulsive, you can't look away.

00:08:07.140 --> 00:08:11.790
And so seductive, you
can't bear to look at it.

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:13.050
I mean, it's that tension.

00:08:13.050 --> 00:08:14.389
But he calls that the sublime.

00:08:14.389 --> 00:08:16.305
So maybe there is something
sublime about that

00:08:16.305 --> 00:08:17.847
that they wanted to
be part, but not.

00:08:17.847 --> 00:08:19.221
They knew something
was going on,

00:08:19.221 --> 00:08:21.040
but they weren't supposed
to be part of it.

00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:23.123
STUDENT 4: I don't know
if we were doing it right.

00:08:23.123 --> 00:08:25.487
But I just had a
little Lego guy, and--

00:08:25.487 --> 00:08:27.570
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Can we
see the little Lego guy?

00:08:27.570 --> 00:08:28.710
STUDENT 4: Yes.

00:08:28.710 --> 00:08:29.535
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Can you describe--

00:08:29.535 --> 00:08:31.160
STUDENT 4: And we
were just playing--

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:33.600
he is a ninja with a hatchet.

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:35.400
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Of course.

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:37.289
STUDENT 4: And so we
playing around with

00:08:37.289 --> 00:08:39.330
whether he had the hatchet
or not had the hatchet

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:41.159
and giving him--

00:08:41.159 --> 00:08:44.650
he had different pictures from
magazines or the newspaper.

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:46.050
And he was in
different contexts.

00:08:46.050 --> 00:08:47.280
And I put him on
the water bubbler

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:49.200
and was playing with him
on the water bubbler.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:50.769
But it was
interesting, and I did

00:08:50.769 --> 00:08:52.560
think that my kids
would have a lot of fun.

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:54.540
My students would have
a lot of fun with it.

00:08:54.540 --> 00:08:56.040
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
So, the hatchet--

00:08:56.040 --> 00:08:58.440
tell me about why with
and without the hatchet?

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:02.280
Is this the accessorizing,
or why was--

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:04.830
STUDENT 4: We had him in
front of the headlines.

00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:07.170
And according to the headline,
if he had the hatchet,

00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:08.777
the headline meant one thing.

00:09:08.777 --> 00:09:10.860
But if he didn't, then it
meant a different thing.

00:09:10.860 --> 00:09:13.537
So that context changed, once
that weapon was introduced.

00:09:13.537 --> 00:09:15.870
STEPHEN CARPENTER: OK, can
you give us an example of one

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:16.800
of those headlines?

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:18.590
STUDENT 4: Someone
won an reward.

00:09:18.590 --> 00:09:20.871
And we put him in front of that.

00:09:20.871 --> 00:09:21.330
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
With the hatchet?

00:09:21.330 --> 00:09:22.950
STUDENT 4: With the hatchet,
which made it a little bit more

00:09:22.950 --> 00:09:23.430
ominous.

00:09:23.430 --> 00:09:24.600
And then without the
hatchet, he was like, yay,

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:25.780
I got this award.

00:09:25.780 --> 00:09:28.071
STEPHEN CARPENTER: [LAUGHS]
So you see in that example,

00:09:28.071 --> 00:09:31.140
you're playing with the
various symbolic meanings that

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:34.160
are referenced with
not just the ninja,

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:36.180
but with that
hatchet and the text.

00:09:36.180 --> 00:09:37.920
So there's the layered readings.

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:41.370
And even that subtle
seemingly innocuous change

00:09:41.370 --> 00:09:45.236
of hatchet or not
hatchet shifts readings--

00:09:45.236 --> 00:09:46.110
shifts meaning there.

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:48.360
It's very powerful.

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:50.540
I hope some of what
we've talked about

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:53.300
gives you beginning
points or places

00:09:53.300 --> 00:09:57.710
of departure for your own
work as educators or artists.

00:09:57.710 --> 00:09:59.360
Continue this work.

00:09:59.360 --> 00:10:01.910
See what else you can trouble,
what other kinds of questions

00:10:01.910 --> 00:10:05.660
you can ask, what other
stories might be told.

00:10:05.660 --> 00:10:09.170
Maybe take the little figures,
and go make some more imagery.

00:10:09.170 --> 00:10:14.660
Maybe find a fire hose, or
attempt other performances.

00:10:14.660 --> 00:10:17.689
Maybe this is an assignment that
would work with your students,

00:10:17.689 --> 00:10:18.480
and give it a shot.

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:21.860
And if it does or if it
doesn't, maybe share it.

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:23.990
Social media, drop me a line.

00:10:23.990 --> 00:10:27.470
We'd love to hear what you're
up to as a ripple from what

00:10:27.470 --> 00:10:29.360
we're doing here.

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:34.160
I said yesterday, and last week,
as an artist, as an educator,

00:10:34.160 --> 00:10:37.310
as a researcher, I
have found that I'm

00:10:37.310 --> 00:10:40.040
more interested in
questioning the answers

00:10:40.040 --> 00:10:42.446
than I am in answering
the questions.

00:10:42.446 --> 00:10:46.540
And for me, the answers are
those social constructs,

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:52.160
those practices, those systems
that people have put in place.

00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:56.180
Sometimes remaining
unquestioned or under analyzed.

00:10:56.180 --> 00:11:00.050
And maybe art making
through social engagement

00:11:00.050 --> 00:11:02.570
is one way to
provoke reflection,

00:11:02.570 --> 00:11:04.790
hoping to discover
something in the process

00:11:04.790 --> 00:11:07.850
about those constructs.

