And then Art Education, which
is essentially primarily

00:11:39.830 --> 00:11:41.510
for K-12 and museum educators.

00:11:41.510 --> 00:11:43.460
And each issue,
they typically have

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:47.010
six articles in here and
then an instruction resource.

00:11:47.010 --> 00:11:48.650
But this particular
special issue

00:11:48.650 --> 00:11:54.380
that came out in July of
2017 is a special issue.

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:57.590
And the call for the theme
was creative activity

00:11:57.590 --> 00:12:00.080
as a human right.

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:02.580
And the editor said,
instead of getting six,

00:12:02.580 --> 00:12:03.980
I want to see how
many I can get.

00:12:03.980 --> 00:12:07.640
So he cut down the length
of the submissions.

00:12:07.640 --> 00:12:10.880
These are shorter pieces,
but they're really

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:12.830
potent little pieces.

00:12:12.830 --> 00:12:14.600
There are so many in here.

00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:18.590
One of the articles in here is
called "Socially Engaged Art

00:12:18.590 --> 00:12:19.130
Education--

00:12:19.130 --> 00:12:21.590
Practices, Processes,
and Possibilities."

00:12:21.590 --> 00:12:28.880
And it's about ceramic water
filters, public performance,

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:30.920
socially engaged art.

00:12:30.920 --> 00:12:35.060
And I co-authored this
with two colleagues,

00:12:35.060 --> 00:12:39.740
Ross Schlemmer, who is a
professor of art education

00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:43.520
in southern Connecticut,
and Erika Hitchcock,

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:45.774
who is a high school art
teacher in Virginia Beach.

00:12:45.774 --> 00:12:47.690
And so the three of us
put our voices together

00:12:47.690 --> 00:12:49.470
to talk about our
experiences here.

00:12:49.470 --> 00:12:51.680
The other piece that I
wanted to share with you

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:54.350
is one that was written
by three art educators

00:12:54.350 --> 00:12:58.792
at Maryland Institute
College of Art in Baltimore.

00:12:58.792 --> 00:13:00.500
I just want to read
the opening paragraph

00:13:00.500 --> 00:13:03.440
to you and then another
excerpt, and then we

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:06.950
can have a final
set of comments.

00:13:06.950 --> 00:13:09.500
Their article is called
"Baltimore Uprising--

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:11.470
Empowering Pedagogy for Change."

00:13:11.470 --> 00:13:15.860
And it was written by Vanessa
López, Adriane Pereira,

00:13:15.860 --> 00:13:17.960
and Shyla Rao.

00:13:17.960 --> 00:13:20.390
"The Baltimore uprising
was in response

00:13:20.390 --> 00:13:23.810
to the death of Freddie
Gray, who was fatally

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:28.490
injured in April 2015 while
in police custody in Baltimore

00:13:28.490 --> 00:13:29.390
City.

00:13:29.390 --> 00:13:31.310
The first evening
of the uprising,

00:13:31.310 --> 00:13:33.350
we were home, glued
to the television,

00:13:33.350 --> 00:13:36.530
communicating with each other
and our pre-service teachers,

00:13:36.530 --> 00:13:39.020
worried about violent
protests that were

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:42.770
erupting in parts of the city."

00:13:42.770 --> 00:13:46.610
That's one of those moments
within your own community

00:13:46.610 --> 00:13:49.620
that changes the community.

00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:54.140
Certainly now, Freddie
Gray's name is well-known.

00:13:54.140 --> 00:13:57.500
And so these three art
education professors,

00:13:57.500 --> 00:14:02.130
who were working with
pre-service teachers,

00:14:02.130 --> 00:14:04.460
were faced with this
real life situation.

00:14:04.460 --> 00:14:07.460
And what is our responsibility,
as art educators, as artists,

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:10.820
as teachers, as citizens
within this community,

00:14:10.820 --> 00:14:16.250
to prepare our teachers to face
these issues, these situations?

00:14:16.250 --> 00:14:18.980
And how do we do so responsibly?

00:14:18.980 --> 00:14:23.880
Not only as community
members and related to them,

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:25.850
to these teachers
as our students,

00:14:25.850 --> 00:14:27.950
but knowing that these
folks are going to become

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:30.080
teachers who might face
similar situations.

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:31.910
And they constructed a pedagogy.

00:14:31.910 --> 00:14:34.220
They called it a pedagogy
for change framework.

00:14:34.220 --> 00:14:37.160
I just want to read briefly what
they wrote and then open it up.

00:14:37.160 --> 00:14:42.110
Because I think this piece
goes to the heart of what

00:14:42.110 --> 00:14:45.910
this theme for
this week has been,

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:48.610
dealing with
difficult situations

00:14:48.610 --> 00:14:51.790
and challenging
social constructs,

00:14:51.790 --> 00:14:55.030
primarily in this
case, police brutality.

00:14:55.030 --> 00:14:57.640
There's elements of white
supremacy and racism

00:14:57.640 --> 00:15:00.140
that flow throughout as well.

00:15:00.140 --> 00:15:04.670
They said, "If we, alongside
our pre-service teachers

00:15:04.670 --> 00:15:06.020
engage with self."

00:15:06.020 --> 00:15:07.080
That's the first piece.

00:15:07.080 --> 00:15:08.960
So there's four
components here, self.

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:11.570
"To understand the
intersections of identities

00:15:11.570 --> 00:15:14.240
from our lived
experiences, examined

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:16.370
through the lens of
the historical context

00:15:16.370 --> 00:15:20.540
of established social injustices
in schools and communities."

00:15:20.540 --> 00:15:22.126
Context being the second.

00:15:22.126 --> 00:15:23.750
"Then we have an
informed understanding

00:15:23.750 --> 00:15:25.490
of these complexities
that," three,

00:15:25.490 --> 00:15:28.850
"students contribute
to the cultural assets

00:15:28.850 --> 00:15:31.400
of every classroom,
with the goal

00:15:31.400 --> 00:15:34.920
of developing a critical for
pedagogy for effecting change

00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:36.140
were deemed necessary."

00:15:36.140 --> 00:15:37.510
So the culmination of self--

00:15:37.510 --> 00:15:40.360
not only teachers, but also
the selves of the students--

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:42.410
in understanding the context--

00:15:42.410 --> 00:15:45.880
social, cultural,
political, locational--

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:48.940
and bringing the students
in there as cultural assets

00:15:48.940 --> 00:15:52.190
within the conversation.

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:56.440
Perhaps the pedagogy
emerges from that formula.

00:15:56.440 --> 00:15:57.790
I think it's a brilliant piece.

00:15:57.790 --> 00:16:01.710
And they walk through each
of those components for you.

